- a. Class A & B
- b. Class C & D
- c. Class E & G

### 56.
Class D controlled airspace, surrounding a Class D towered airport, is depicted on an aeronautical chart as:

- a. A blue dashed circle, with a normal upper limit of 2500 feet AGL, usually 10 nautical miles in diameter
- b. A magenta dashed circle, with a vertical limit at overlying controlled airspace, usually 10 nautical miles in diameter
- c. Two thick magenta solid concentric circles, with a vertical limit given in hundreds of feet MSL, usually 20 nautical miles in diameter
- d. Several thick blue solid concentric circles, with a vertical limit given in hundreds of feet MSL, associated with a thin solid magenta circle (Mode C transponder veil) usually 60 nautical miles in diameter

### 57.
According to FAR Part 103, what are the minimum visibility and cloud clearance requirements when flying in Class E controlled airspace below 10,000 feet MSL?

- a. 1 statute mile visibility, remaining clear of clouds
- b. 3 statute miles visibility, remaining clear of clouds
- c. 3 statute miles visibility, remaining 50 feet below, 100 feet above, and 200 feet horizontally away from clouds
- d. 3 statute miles visibility, remaining 500 feet below, 1000 feet above, and 2000 feet horizontally away from clouds

### 58.
A Temporary Flight Restriction (TFR), which can put in place by the federal government with short notice to prohibit flight over a geographical area due to presidential visits, national security concerns, large sporting events, natural disasters, accident investigation, etc., applies only to regular aircraft, and not to hang gliders, paragliders, or ultralights.

- a. True
- b. False

